      "writtenOn": "2017-08-24T22:02:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I personally have a great fondness for the interface on top of rsync\u0027s src and dst. From the manpage:\n\n              rsync -avz foo:src/bar /data/tmp\n\n       This would recursively transfer all files from the directory src/bar on\n       the  machine foo into the /data/tmp/bar directory on the local machine.\n...\n       A  trailing slash on the source changes this behavior to avoid creating\n       an additional directory level at the destination.  You can think  of  a\n       trailing / on a source as meaning \"copy the contents of this directory\"\n       as opposed to \"copy the directory by  name\",  but  in  both  cases  the\n       attributes  of the containing directory are transferred to the contain‐\n       ing directory on the destination.  In other words, each of the  follow‐\n       ing  commands copies the files in the same way, [...]:\n\n              rsync -av /src/foo /dest\n              rsync -av /src/foo/ /dest/foo\n\nWhen there are conflicts, the default behavior is that rsync:\n* will *not* replace directories with a *file* of the same name (thereby deleting the directory), and\n* will replace files with files of the same name\n\nThere are three flags that changes this behavior:\n\n            --ignore-existing       skip updating files that exist on receiver\n        -u, --update                skip files that are newer on the receiver (by mtime)\n            --force                 force deletion of dirs even if not empty\n\nI don\u0027t think that we really need to worry about --update and --force. Perhaps something like --ignore-existing would be worthwhile, though. A bool parameter?\n\nPerhaps also merge PutFile and PutTree into \"PutPath\".",
      "parentUuid": "d1ea1841_8dd3cd64",
      "revId": "fb4f7f5913348340bdcd63d50947961a284c0156",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
